## What web map services are

Web map services (WMS, WMTS, XYZ tiles) are remote map layers hosted on a server that you can stream directly into your GIS software or web application without downloading any files. Instead of storing the data locally, you connect to a URL and the tiles are rendered on demand.

This makes them ideal for basemaps, imagery, elevation, and reference layers that would be impractical to download and store — such as global satellite imagery or worldwide terrain data.

## Desktop GIS: QGIS and ArcGIS Pro

Both QGIS and ArcGIS Pro support adding XYZ tile services directly to your map as background or reference layers.

### Add World Hillshade in QGIS

**Level:** Beginner · **Time:** 5 minutes

1. Open the **Browser** panel in QGIS (View → Panels → Browser).
2. Right-click **XYZ Tiles** and select **New Connection**.
3. Enter the following:
   - **Name:** World Hillshade
   - **URL:** `https://server.arcgisonline.com/ArcGIS/rest/services/World_Hillshade/MapServer/tile/{z}/{y}/{x}`
4. Click **OK**.
5. Double-click the new connection in the Browser panel to add it to your map.

The hillshade layer will appear as a grayscale relief background. Place it beneath your vector layers for clean terrain context.

### Add World Imagery in ArcGIS Pro

**Level:** Beginner · **Time:** 5 minutes

1. Open ArcGIS Pro with an active map.
2. Go to **Map → Add Data → Data From Path**.
3. Paste the following URL:
   `https://server.arcgisonline.com/ArcGIS/rest/services/World_Imagery/MapServer`
4. Click **OK**.
5. Add your vector layers on top of the imagery layer.

World Imagery provides high-resolution satellite and aerial photography for visual inspection and digitizing.

## OpenLayers: Simple web map

OpenLayers is a JavaScript library for embedding interactive maps in web pages. The following example creates a map centered on Guyana using OpenStreetMap tiles, with a marker at Georgetown.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Guyana Map - OpenStreetMap</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/ol/ol.css">
  <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/ol/dist/ol.js"></script>
  <style>
    #map { width: 100%; height: 500px; border-radius: 8px; margin-top: 10px; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <div id="map"></div>
  <script>
    const map = new ol.Map({
      target: 'map',
      layers: [
        new ol.layer.Tile({ source: new ol.source.OSM() })
      ],
      view: new ol.View({
        center: ol.proj.fromLonLat([-58.5, 4.8]),
        zoom: 6
      })
    });

    // Georgetown marker
    const marker = new ol.Feature({
      geometry: new ol.geom.Point(ol.proj.fromLonLat([-58.155, 6.805]))
    });
    marker.setStyle(new ol.style.Style({
      image: new ol.style.Circle({
        radius: 7,
        fill: new ol.style.Fill({ color: '#E8C547' }),
        stroke: new ol.style.Stroke({ color: '#2E5E4A', width: 2 })
      })
    }));
    const markerLayer = new ol.layer.Vector({
      source: new ol.source.Vector({ features: [marker] })
    });
    map.addLayer(markerLayer);
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

## OpenLayers: Multiple web services

This example combines OpenStreetMap with an Esri World Hillshade overlay, with toggle buttons to switch layers on and off.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Guyana Map - Multiple Web Services</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/ol/ol.css">
  <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/ol/dist/ol.js"></script>
  <style>
    #map { width: 100%; height: 500px; border-radius: 8px; margin-top: 10px; }
    .controls { margin-bottom: 12px; }
    button {
      margin: 4px; padding: 6px 12px;
      background: #2E5E4A; color: white;
      border: none; border-radius: 4px; cursor: pointer;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <div class="controls">
    <button onclick="toggleOSM()">Toggle OpenStreetMap</button>
    <button onclick="toggleHillshade()">Toggle Hillshade</button>
    <button onclick="resetView()">Reset View</button>
  </div>
  <div id="map"></div>
  <script>
    const osmLayer = new ol.layer.Tile({
      source: new ol.source.OSM(),
      visible: true
    });
    const hillshadeLayer = new ol.layer.Tile({
      source: new ol.source.XYZ({
        url: 'https://server.arcgisonline.com/ArcGIS/rest/services/World_Hillshade/MapServer/tile/{z}/{y}/{x}',
        attributions: '© Esri, USGS'
      }),
      opacity: 0.7,
      visible: true
    });
    const map = new ol.Map({
      target: 'map',
      layers: [osmLayer, hillshadeLayer],
      view: new ol.View({
        center: ol.proj.fromLonLat([-58.5, 4.8]),
        zoom: 6
      })
    });
    function toggleOSM() { osmLayer.setVisible(!osmLayer.getVisible()); }
    function toggleHillshade() { hillshadeLayer.setVisible(!hillshadeLayer.getVisible()); }
    function resetView() {
      map.getView().setCenter(ol.proj.fromLonLat([-58.5, 4.8]));
      map.getView().setZoom(6);
    }
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

## Leaflet: World Imagery with layer control

Leaflet is a lighter alternative to OpenLayers. This example adds Esri World Imagery as the default basemap with OpenStreetMap as a switchable option, plus markers for Georgetown and New Amsterdam.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Guyana Map - Leaflet</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://unpkg.com/leaflet/dist/leaflet.css">
  <script src="https://unpkg.com/leaflet/dist/leaflet.js"></script>
  <style>
    #map { width: 100%; height: 500px; border-radius: 8px; margin-top: 10px; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <div id="map"></div>
  <script>
    var map = L.map('map').setView([4.8, -58.5], 6);

    var imagery = L.tileLayer(
      'https://server.arcgisonline.com/ArcGIS/rest/services/World_Imagery/MapServer/tile/{z}/{y}/{x}',
      { maxZoom: 19, attribution: '© Esri, Maxar, Earthstar Geographics' }
    ).addTo(map);

    var osm = L.tileLayer(
      'https://{s}.tile.openstreetmap.org/{z}/{x}/{y}.png',
      { maxZoom: 19, attribution: '© OpenStreetMap contributors' }
    );

    L.control.layers(
      { 'World Imagery': imagery, 'OpenStreetMap': osm }
    ).addTo(map);

    L.marker([6.805, -58.155]).addTo(map)
      .bindPopup('<b>Georgetown</b><br>Capital of Guyana');
    L.marker([6.4, -58.6]).addTo(map)
      .bindPopup('<b>New Amsterdam</b><br>East Berbice-Corentyne');

    L.control.scale().addTo(map);
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

> **Note:** Leaflet is the same mapping library used by Guynode's own GIS Viewer and Locator pages. If you are familiar with these examples, you already understand the foundation of how those tools work.

## Common issues and fixes

**Tiles don't load**
Check that the URL pattern uses `{z}/{y}/{x}` or `{z}/{x}/{y}` in the correct order for the service. Verify HTTPS is used — HTTP tile requests are blocked on secure pages.

**Blank or grey map**
Confirm your internet connection. Open the browser developer console (F12) and look for CORS errors or failed network requests. Try substituting a different service to isolate whether the issue is the URL or the environment.

**Permission errors**
Some services require authentication tokens or API keys. Use the public services listed in the Global Map Services reference rather than authenticated endpoints for learning purposes.

**Distorted or misaligned layers**
Web map tile services use the Web Mercator projection (EPSG:3857) by default. Ensure your desktop GIS project CRS is set to EPSG:3857 when combining XYZ tile services with local vector data, or confirm that on-the-fly reprojection is enabled.
